The PISA Data¶

By Senga Mukanda¶

Introduction¶

In this first part, I will conduct an exploratory data analysis on a dataset of my choice. I will then use Python data science and data visualization libraries to explore the datasets variables and understand the datas structure, oddities, patterns, and relationships.

The dataset that I chose to explore was the PISA 2012 assessment.

PISA Data: PISA is a survey of students' skills and knowledge as they approach the end of compulsory education. This survey examines

  • how well students have learned the school curriculum,
  • how well prepared they are for life beyond school.

PISA is a unique global survey that examines how well prepared 15 year old students are for life after they have completed school. Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • The original PISA dataset consisted of 485,490 rows and 635 columns. But since my laptop doesn't have the RAM to load all the rows and columns. I chose to load only the columns of interest for me and saved them in a new dataframe that i will be using for this analysis. My datset still consists of the same number of rows but now I only have 12 columns.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

  • I want to take a look at what factors have an effect on the overall scores in Maths (PV1MATH , PV2MATH, PV3MATH, PV4MATH, PV5MATH), Reading (PV1READ, PV2READ, PV3READ, PV4READ, PV5READ), and Science (PV1SCIE, PV2SCIE, PV3SCIE, PV4SCIE, PV5SCIE) of the students that participate in these tests.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • There are indeed a lot of factors that would play a role in this, but I will only be taking a look at whether gender (ST04Q01) or birth year (ST03Q02) plays a role, or if the country (CNT) where the test is taken contributes as well and I will also look at if the parents job status (ST15Q01 and ST19Q01) plays a role.

Clean all of the issues you documented while assessing. Perform this cleaning in the "Cleaning Data" section.

# Before I clean my dataset I first want to make a copy so that way I can preserve the original data.
pisa_data_clean = pisa_data.copy()
In [9]:
# First I want to create columns for the average scores of maths, science and reading
pisa_data_clean['Math Score Average'] = (pisa_data_clean['PV1MATH'] + pisa_data_clean['PV2MATH'] + pisa_data_clean['PV3MATH'] + pisa_data_clean['PV4MATH'] + pisa_data_clean['PV5MATH']) / 5
pisa_data_clean['Reading Score Average'] = (pisa_data_clean['PV1READ'] + pisa_data_clean['PV2READ'] + pisa_data_clean['PV3READ'] + pisa_data_clean['PV4READ'] + pisa_data_clean['PV5READ']) / 5
pisa_data_clean['Science Score Average'] = (pisa_data_clean['PV1SCIE'] + pisa_data_clean['PV2SCIE'] + pisa_data_clean['PV3SCIE'] + pisa_data_clean['PV4SCIE'] + pisa_data_clean['PV5SCIE']) / 5

# Second I want to create a coloumn for the maximum scores of maths, reading and science
pisa_data_clean['Maximum Math Score'] = pisa_data_clean[['PV1MATH','PV2MATH', 'PV3MATH', 'PV4MATH', 'PV5MATH']].max(axis=1)
pisa_data_clean['Maximum Reading Score'] = pisa_data_clean[['PV1READ', 'PV2READ', 'PV3READ', 'PV4READ', 'PV5READ']].max(axis=1)
pisa_data_clean['Maximum Science Score'] = pisa_data_clean[['PV1SCIE', 'PV2SCIE', 'PV3SCIE', 'PV4SCIE', 'PV5SCIE']].max(axis=1)

# This will create a function that allows us to combine the observation of the mothers and fathers job status as one
# observation for the household.
def work_status(mom_work,dad_work):  
    """ 
    This function will rename the parents job status to make it more understandable
    """    
# Other stands for e.g. home duties, retired
    
    if mom_work == '2' and dad_work == '2':
        status = 'Both other'
    elif mom_work == '2' and dad_work == '0':
        status = 'only mom other'
    elif mom_work == '0' and dad_work == '2':
        status = 'Only dad other'
    elif mom_work == '4' and dad_work == '4':
        status = 'Both looking for work'
 #Both Parents are working   
    elif (mom_work == '1' and dad_work == '1') or (mom_work == '1' and dad_work == '3'):
        status = 'Both working'
    elif (mom_work == '3' and dad_work == '3') or (mom_work == '3' and dad_work == '1'):
        status = 'Both working'
# Only mom is working       
    elif (mom_work == '1' and dad_work == '0') or (mom_work == '3' and dad_work == '0'):
        status = 'Only mom working'
    elif (mom_work == '1' and dad_work == '2') or (mom_work == '3' and dad_work == '2'):
        status = 'Only mom working'
    elif (mom_work == '1' and dad_work == '4') or (mom_work == '3' and dad_work == '4'):
        status = 'Only mom working'
# Only dad is working        
    elif (mom_work == '0' and dad_work == '1') or (mom_work == '0' and dad_work == '3'):
        status = 'Only dad working'
    elif (mom_work == '2' and dad_work == '1') or (mom_work == '2' and dad_work == '3'):
        status = 'Only dad working'
    elif (mom_work == '4' and dad_work == '1') or (mom_work == '4' and dad_work == '3'):
        status = 'Only dad working'   
# only one parent is looking for work
    elif (mom_work == '4' and dad_work == '0') or (mom_work == '4' and dad_work == '2'):
        status = 'Only mom looking for work'
    elif (mom_work == '0' and dad_work == '4') or (mom_work == '2' and dad_work == '4'):
        status = 'Only dad looking for work'   
    else:
        status = 'Unknown'
    return status

# This code will create a new column where our function will be applied
pisa_data_clean["parents_job_status"] = pisa_data_clean.apply(lambda x: work_status(x["mom_work"],x["dad_work"]), axis=1)

In [37]:
# Because with some questions I want to draw a bar graph, I will create a function that will allow me to do that
# so that I can call that function anytime I want to draw a graph
def bargraph_plot(x, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    """
    This function will plot a bargraph based on the parameters passed on:
    x (string): the series you want to plot
    xlabel (category): the label on the x-axis
    ylabel (string): the label on the y-axis
    title(string): the title of the graph
    """
    # Set the style of your graph
    mplt.style.use('fivethirtyeight')
    sb.set_context("notebook")
    
    # Rotate the x-axis ticks so that they don't overlap
    mplt.xticks(rotation = 15)
    
    # Set the plot's title and labels
    mplt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize=10)
    mplt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize=10)
    mplt.title(title, fontsize=10)
    
    plot = x.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(10,6))
    return plot

Conclusions¶

When I started with my exploration I was mainly interested in the factors that contributes to the total averages of Math, Reading and Science.

I was majorly interested on how the Parents Work Status would affect the score averages for the students, so to say in the least I was a bit dissapointed that I didn't get the outcome I was looking for.

Even though Birth Year was one of my factors of interest, I saw that I would need other factors which I did not include in my dataset. So this also turned out to not give me any promising outcome because there was not much information I could get from it.

The two factors that gave me the most results were Gender and Country Code suprisingly enough they were the two factors I thought would not contribute much to the overall averages.

I learned that more females participated in the survey than males. Since the females performed better than the males when it came to Reading any country that had more female participants would have a better average in that. The male participants performed better than the females when it came to Math and so any country that had more male participants would have a better average in that. They performed evenly equal when it came to Science, so the overall average depended on the number of gender participation when it came to that. This is because science is a mixture of both reading and maths so if you have more females the average favors them and vice-versa.

Limitations¶

  • This dataset is very large and requires a PC with a very large RAM in order to open it directly and not as a compressed zip folder.
  • Because of the file size, I was limited to only pick a few columns to work with and this caused my exploration to only focus on what I picked.

Given an oppurtunity I would explore every factors that I could because this dataset has a lot to explore but because of my limitations could only explore a few. The good thing is this test is written every year by different candidates so there's always going to be something new to look forward to if you want to work with the PISA dataset.
